This method should work to order a DataGrid based on a provided column and direction. However, there are a few things that can prevent the sorting from working correctly:

1. The data in the DataGrid may not implement the ICollectionView interface required for sorting. Make sure the ItemsSource property of the DataGrid is set to a collection that supports sorting.

2. The column name parameter may not match the actual column name in the DataGrid. Double-check that the column name is correct and matches the binding property of the column.

3. There may be multiple SortDescriptions already applied to the DataGrid. You can clear them before adding a new one: datagrid.Items.SortDescriptions.Clear(); 

4. The sorting may not be updating the UI. Make sure the DataGrid is being refreshed after sorting by calling datagrid.Items.Refresh(); 

With these considerations in mind, you can modify the method to look like this:

public static void OrderDataGrid(DataGrid datagrid, string column, ListSortDirection direction = ListSortDirection.Ascending)
{
    ICollectionView view = CollectionViewSource.GetDefaultView(datagrid.ItemsSource);
    view.SortDescriptions.Clear(); // clear existing sorting
    view.SortDescriptions.Add(new SortDescription(column, direction));
    view.Refresh(); // update UI
}

If the "view" variable is null, it means that the ItemsSource property of the DataGrid is not set to a collection that implements the ICollectionView interface required for sorting.

To fix this, you should check that the ItemsSource property is set correctly before calling the OrderDataGrid method. You can also modify the method to handle cases where ItemsSource is null by adding a null check:

```
public static void OrderDataGrid(DataGrid datagrid, string column, ListSortDirection direction = ListSortDirection.Ascending)
{
    if (datagrid.ItemsSource == null)
    {
        return;
    }
    ICollectionView view = CollectionViewSource.GetDefaultView(datagrid.ItemsSource);
    if (view == null)
    {
        view = new ListCollectionView(datagrid.ItemsSource as IList);
    }
    view.SortDescriptions.Clear(); // clear existing sorting
    view.SortDescriptions.Add(new SortDescription(column, direction));
    view.Refresh(); // update UI
}
```

This code first checks that ItemsSource is not null before attempting to create a ICollectionView instance. If the default view for the collection is null, it creates a new ListCollectionView instead. This ensures that the method works even if the collection does not implement ICollectionView directly.

If your collection does not implement the ICollectionView interface, you can create a new ListCollectionView object to enable sorting. The ListCollectionView class is a concrete implementation of the ICollectionView interface that works with IList collections like ObservableCollection or List.

Here's an updated version of the OrderDataGrid method that creates a new ListCollectionView if the default view is null:

```
public static void OrderDataGrid(DataGrid datagrid, string column, ListSortDirection direction = ListSortDirection.Ascending)
{
    if (datagrid.ItemsSource == null)
    {
        return;
    }
    ICollectionView view = CollectionViewSource.GetDefaultView(datagrid.ItemsSource);
    if (view == null)
    {
        view = new ListCollectionView(datagrid.ItemsSource as IList);
    }
    view.SortDescriptions.Clear(); // clear existing sorting
    view.SortDescriptions.Add(new SortDescription(column, direction));
    view.Refresh(); // update UI
}
```

This code first checks if the default view is null and creates a new ListCollectionView using the ItemsSource collection as the constructor argument. The OrderDataGrid method then sets the SortDescriptions property on the view object to the desired column and direction before updating the UI with the Refresh method.

Note that the ListCollectionView is a separate object from the original collection, so changes made to the original collection will not automatically update the view. You'll need to recreate the ListCollectionView object or update the existing object when the collection changes.

